{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502202"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1835"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1835"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.18,0.06,0.11,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115567"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1835"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49156"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115567"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-week history of fever, chest pain, and cough. Over the past two weeks, he has developed shortness of breath, and his cough has changed from dry to productive with foul-smelling sputum. His symptoms began after a seizure and have worsened since then. He has also noticed night sweats and weight loss over the past two weeks. He has no significant medical history apart from epilepsy, for which he takes sodium valproate. He does not smoke and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 129/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20 breaths/min, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung abscess","Tuberculosis","Lung cancer","Bronchiectasis","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and chest X-ray findings in this case are most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Elung abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. The CXR shows air space shadowing in the upper segment of the lower lobe of the right lung. The right main bronchus has a larger luminal diameter and a more vertical trajectory than the left main bronchus, making it more susceptible to aspirated content. The superior segment of the lower lobe or the posterior segment of the upper lobe are the most common to be involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history suggests aspiration pneumonia, which likely occurred during the seizure four weeks ago. Lung abscess is a common complication of aspiration pneumonia, particularly when left untreated. The symptoms of productive cough with foul-smelling sputum, fever, chest pain, shortness of breath, night sweats, and weight loss are all characteristic of a lung abscess. Other symptoms include high-grade fever, tachypnea and fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is a contagious infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis that primarily affects the lungs but can also affect other organs, including the bones, brain, and spine. It can present with similar symptoms, including cough, fever, night sweats, and weight loss. However, the acute onset following a seizure, the rapid progression of symptoms and high fever (rather than a low-grade fever) make tuberculosis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this 27-year-old non-smoker. While lung cancer can cause similar symptoms, including a persistent cough, hemoptysis, hoarseness, chest pain, and weight loss, it typically has a more insidious onset and is rare in young, non-smoking individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition characterised by permanent dilation of the airways. Bronchiectasis may present similarly with a productive cough, chest pain, fevers, night sweats and weight loss; however, the short timeline and rapid progression of symptoms make this less likely. Additionally, it is often associated with a history of recurrent respiratory infections over months to years, and the CXR would show dilated airways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a multisystem inflammatory disorder that can manifest as non-caseating granulomas predominantly in the lungs and intrathoracic lymph nodes. However, it typically presents with a dry cough rather than a productive one, and the acute onset following a seizure is not characteristic of sarcoidosis. Sarcoidosis also tends to have a more gradual onset and a more chronic course, and may have other symptoms such as arthralgia, rash on the lower legs, blurred vision, arrhythmias, palpitations or eye pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lung abscess is a common complication of aspiration pneumonia.","Aspiration pneumonia commonly affects the right lung due to the anatomy of the right main bronchus.","Lung abscess typically presents with productive cough, foul-smelling sputum, fever, chest pain, and systemic symptoms."],"references":["van Brummelen SE, Melles D, van der Eerden M. [A lung abscess caused by bad teeth]. Ned Tijdschr Tandheelkd. 2018 Jul;125(7-8):384-387.","Neill S, Dean N. Aspiration pneumonia and pneumonitis: a spectrum of infectious/noninfectious diseases affecting the lung. Curr Opin Infect Dis. 2019 Apr;32(2):152-157."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1835"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18312"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18312"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/477d4c64-c0ae-422d-a94f-9a5e3f794b97.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/477d4c64-c0ae-422d-a94f-9a5e3f794b97.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":736,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97570"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T13:22:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T13:24:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1835"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115567"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships"